<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Comic Sans MS, Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, MS Sans" COLOR="#400000">Originally posted by Stormwaltz on 09-20-1999 10:59 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">*cough* I'm a designer, so I'm not really "buzz," but I can give a definite answer...

Sorry, Kaeden. Truly effective rogue skills would require new code, and that has to wait until v1.1, which only happens if 1.0 sells well. There's really no way to play a true rogue in AC, which is why the Rogue template was renamed Vagabond. Vagabond said "bum" to me, but I was outvoted...

Long ago, there were plans for stealth rolls to see/hear other players, or to be detected by monsters. Both could be surprise-attacked/backstabbed. Far away in a happier land, the designers dreamed of skills that allowed would-be thieves to scale the walls of guarded houses, and enter the second floor windows.

Know those big upper stabbing limbs on the Olthoi? Originally, those were climbing arms, and Olthoi hives were to be huge, vertical tubes under "ant hill" surface mounds, with tunnels leading off from the core. Unfortunately, the code as it was would allow a creature/player to start climbing even with no wall present - imagine a two-ton Olthoi noble scaling the air in front of you.

Why didn't it simply get fixed? Not enough dev time. If AC was the game everyone had dreamed it would be when they started, nothing else could have held a candle to it until 2005. Seriously - I just got a peek at the old-old 1996/7 design docs. They're amazing.

- Chris (frustrated Bum... Er, "Vagabond")

------------------
** Turbine Entertainment Software doesn't know I said this. Shh.

[This message has been edited by Stormwaltz (edited September 20, 1999).]</TEXTAREA>
